<paragraph blockId="79.[151,1436,1685,2034]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1973,1998]" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Leaf mine.</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[344,440,1973,1998]" captionStart="FIGURES 189–199" captionStartId="121.[151,264,1660,1683]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetId="figure@121.[151,1437,193,1639]" captionTargetPageId="121" captionText="FIGURES 189–199. leaf mines; 189: Phytomyza hatfieldae spec. nov. in Osmorhiza claytonii; 190: P. hydrophyllivora spec. nov. in Hydrophyllum canadense; 191: P. hydrophyllivora in Hydrophyllum virginianum (yellow puparium at tip of leaf serration, upper right); 192: P. linnaeae (Griffiths) in Linnaea borealis (transmitted light); 193: P. loewii Hendel in Clematis virginiana; 194: P. minuscula Goureau in Thalictrum pubescens; 195: P. omlandi Scheffer &amp; Lonsdale in Gelsemium sempervirens; 196: P. palmeri spec. nov. in Symphoricarpos orbiculatus (transmitted light; puparium at upper left); 197: P. palustris spec. nov. in Micranthes pensylvanica; 198: same, five brown puparia in blisters on lower leaf surface (whitish object along left side of midrib is a coniopterygid cocoon); 199: P. penstemonis Spencer in Penstemon digitalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1452959/files/figure.png" pageId="79" pageNumber="80">Fig. 199</figureCitation>
) Whitish, entirely linear; primarily on the upper surface but often with the final portion on the lower surface; frass in dark strips along the sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="80.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,151,176]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Puparium.</emphasis>
White (yellowish according to 
<bibRefCitation box="[705,894,151,176]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81" refId="ref103273" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1969) The Agromyzidae of Canada and Alaska. Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada, 64, 1 - 311. https: // doi. org / 10.4039 / entm 10164 fv" type="journal article">Spencer (1969))</bibRefCitation>
, formed within the leaf, the anterior spiracles projecting ventrally through the lower epidermis.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="80" pageNumber="81" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="80.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,223,248]" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry box="[359,419,224,248]" name="United States of America" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">USA</collectingCountry>
: CA, *CT, MS, *NY; 
<collectingCountry box="[665,754,223,248]" name="Canada" pageId="80" pageNumber="81">Canada</collectingCountry>
: AB. We have seen probable mines of this species (including photographs submitted to www.BugGuide.net) in AZ and WI.
</paragraph>
